<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1058,607,659]" pageId="27" pageNumber="986">
D i a g n o s i s: Within 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opitz" authorityYear="1997" box="[432,564,607,628]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Megatrachys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="986" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[432,564,607,628]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="986">Megatrachys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
OPITZ, this is the only known species whose specimens lack a cranial wisp of black setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1059,673,1031]" pageId="27" pageNumber="986">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Size: Length 
<quantity box="[516,597,673,695]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" pageId="27" pageNumber="986" unit="mm" value="6.5">6.5 mm</quantity>
; width 2.0 mm. Form: As in 
<figureCitation box="[895,980,673,695]" captionStart="Figs 302-305" captionStartId="103.[151,191,1520,1542]" captionTargetBox="[151,1059,197,1504]" captionTargetId="figure@103.[151,1059,197,1504]" captionTargetPageId="103" captionText="Figs 302-305: Habitus; (302) Megatrachys irrasis; (303) Plocamocera catalexis; (304) Pyticeroides brevitubulus; (305) P. desodes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746812" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746812/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="986">Fig. 302</figureCitation>
. Color: Cranium and pronotum dark castaneous; antennae bicolorous, scape testaceous, remainder of antenna brown; pterothorax and abdominal sternites black; elytra mostly brown, side areas dark brown, with short wisps of black setae; legs bicolorous, femora, tibiae, and tarsi with portions of yellow and brown. Head: Cranium coarsely sculptured, highly setose; antenna (
<figureCitation box="[396,472,813,835]" captionStart="Figs 61-91" captionStartId="73.[151,191,1343,1365]" captionTargetBox="[151,1033,198,1310]" captionTargetId="figure@73.[151,1059,198,1328]" captionTargetPageId="73" captionText="Figs 61-91: Antennae; (61) Madoniella muralla; (62) M. nota; (63) M. acicula; (64) M. aspera; (65) M. baja; (66) M. delta; (67) Amboakis bermejo; (68) Pujoliclerus variolus; (69) Megatrachys irrasis; (70) Cregya arima; (71) Nelsopelonium aspikelum; (72) Cregya vicosa; (73) Pujoliclerus abditus; (74) P. dexus; (75) Cregya triguttula; (76) Pyticeroides brevitubulus; (77) Pujoliclerus lasiosus; (78) Cregya biguttula; (79) Sirpa acara; (80) Parapelonides naranjo; (81) Cregya livida; (82) Amboakis collucoatis; (83) Ampleris jatai; (84) Megaphloeus yasuni; (85) Pelonium implacide, male; (86) Epiphloeus prolixicornus; (87) Pelonium implacide, female; (88) Epiphloeus mantillerii; (89) Amboakis mitaraka; (90) Ellipotoma makrosa; (91) Cregya maura." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746752" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746752/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="986">Fig. 69</figureCitation>
) capitate, funicular antennomeres filiform, progressively shorter towards capitulum, capitular antennomeres 8 and 9 triangular, antennomere 10 ovoid; eyes large, finely facetted, eye slightly narrower than frons (EW/FW 25/28). Thorax: Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[355,443,897,919]" captionStart="Figs 118-133" captionStartId="76.[151,191,1373,1395]" captionTargetBox="[152,1050,202,1340]" captionTargetId="figure@76.[152,1056,202,1357]" captionTargetPageId="76" captionText="Figs 118-133: Pronota; (118) Pujoliclerus abditus; (119) Nelsopelonium aspikelum; (120) Parapelonides naranjo; (121) Pujoliclerus lasiosus; (122) Neorthopleura rubra; (123) Pujoliclerus ariquemes; (124) Ichnea cerinis; (125) Ampleris amazon; (126) Pujoliclerus abditus; (127) P. dexsus; (128) Sirpa acara; (129) Madoniella aspera; (130) Pelonium tayrona; (131) Megatrachys irrasis; (132) Ordinis taxis; (133) Pujoliclerus cnecostus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746758" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746758/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="986">Fig. 131</figureCitation>
) quadrate, highly setose, somewhat corrugated, disc deeply concave paralaterally near pronotal collar; discal and lateral trichobothria well developed (PW/PL 70/70); elytral disc corrugated; asetiferous punctures large and randomly distributed, small brown and yellow setal wisps present throughout elytral disc (EL/EW 290/55); anterior margin of protibia with 4 spines. Abdomen: Pygidium scutiform.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,758,1046,1068]" box="[151,758,1046,1068]" pageId="27" pageNumber="986">Variation: The available specimens are quite homogeneous.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1058,1083,1135]" pageId="27" pageNumber="986">N a t u r a l H i s t o r y: The available specimens were collected in a Malaise trap during periods of 13-31-III, 30-VII-17-VIII, and 17-VIII-1-IX.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,783,1149,1171]" box="[151,783,1149,1171]" pageId="27" pageNumber="986">D i s t r i b u t i o n: ThisspeciesisknownfromColombia.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1058,1185,1263]" pageId="27" pageNumber="986">
E t y m o l o g y: The trivial name, 
<emphasis box="[539,605,1186,1207]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="986">irrasis</emphasis>
, is a Latin adjective derived from 
<emphasis box="[956,1028,1186,1207]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="986">irrasus</emphasis>
(= unpolished); with reference to corrugated condition of the surface of the pronotal and elytral discs.
</paragraph>
